y, Northamptonshire, England","Great Bromley, Essex, England":"Great Bromley, Essex, England","St John's Abbey, Colchester, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"St John's Abbey, Colchester, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Wakerley, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wakerley, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Lanvallei II was born in 1155, in Wakerley, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, William de Langvalei I, was 30 and his mother, Gunnora St Clare, was 26. He married Hawise Bocland about 1179, in Wakerley, Northamptonshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died on 18 May 1205, in his hometown, at the age of 50, and was buried in St John's Abbey, Colchester, Essex, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1155–18 May 1205":"1155–18. mai 1205","1155–1205":"1155–1205","1157–1233":"1157–1233","1180–1217":"1180–1217","1190–1219":"1190–1219","1125–1180":"1125–1180","1130–Female":"1130–Surnud","1190":"1190","about 1161":"umbes 1161","18 May 1205":"18. mai 1205","1130":"1130","1180":"1180","1217":"1217","1205":"1205","1125":"1125","1157":"1157","1233":"1233","1155":"1155","about 1179":"umbes 1179","1219":"1219","Wakerley, Northamptonshire, England":"Wakerley, Northamptonshire, England","Great Bromley, Essex, England":"Great Bromley, Essex, England","St John's Abbey, Colchester, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"St John's Abbey, Colchester, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wakerley, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wakerley, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1155–18 May 1205":"1155–18. toukokuuta 1205","1155–1205":"1155–1205","1157–1233":"1157–1233","1180–1217":"1180–1217","1190–1219":"1190–1219","1125–1180":"1125–1180","1130–Female":"1130–Kuollut","1190":"1190","about 1161":"noin 1161","18 May 1205":"18. toukokuuta 1205","1130":"1130","1180":"1180","1217":"1217","1205":"1205","1125":"1125","1157":"1157","1233":"1233","1155":"1155","about 1179":"noin 1179","1219":"1219","Wakerley, Northamptonshire, England":"Wakerley, Northamptonshire, England","Great Bromley, Essex, England":"Great Bromley, Essex, England","St John's Abbey, Colchester, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"St John's Abbey, Colchester, Essex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Wakerley, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wakerley, Northamptonshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1155–18 May 1205":"1155–18 mai 1205","1155–1205":"1155–1205","1157–1233":"1157–1233","1180–1217"